article.description:
Tamika Catchings had 11 points and nine rebounds
to lead a balanced attack for the Indiana Fever in their 75-60 victory over the Chicago Sky on Friday night.
article.headline: Versatile Catchings fuels Fever past Sky
article.linkText: Sky's not the limit in 15-point drubbing by Fever
article.story:
CHICAGO (AP) -- Tamika Catchings wanted to put on a good show for
her hometown fans.

Catchings scored 11 points with seven rebounds, six assists and
four steals to help keep the Indiana Fever undefeated with a 75-60
victory over the Chicago Sky on Friday night.

"Tonight I wanted to make so much happen because I want some of
the people who haven't had the chance to go to Indiana to get a
chance to see me," Catchings said.

The Fever (3-0) shot 50 percent from the field in the first half
-- including 9-for-13 in the second quarter -- but only took a
four-point lead into halftime. The Sky (1-2) was able to stay close
by outrebounding the Fever by eight in the first half.

"We hang our hat on our defense and our rebounding," Fever
coach Brian Winters said. "In the first half I felt that we didn't
rebound."

The Fever came out strong in the third quarter, limiting Chicago
to 3-for-20 from the field. Indiana also out rebounded the Sky 18-8
in the third and were able to get some easy baskets in transition.

"In the second half we didn't allow them those second-chance
points and we got out in transition," Winters said.

Four Indiana players joined Catchings in double-figures.

Tamika Whitmore had 10 points, seven rebounds and four steals
for Indiana. Tan White had 14 points while Linda Frohlich and Anna
DeForge each added 10.

Jia Perkins scored 16 points to lead the Sky (1-2). Candice
Dupree added 11 points and five rebounds.

"I think they were playing good defense but I just think that
we were missing shots that we normally would hit," Perkins said.
"We were missing some pretty wide open stuff."

The Sky shot 32.9 percent from the field and were 3-of-14 from
behind the 3-point arc.

"This game looks pretty good when you make shots and looks
pretty ugly when you don't," Sky coach Dave Cowens said.

Whitmore keyed a 9-0 run with six straight points as Indiana
took a 49-38 lead with 3:52 remaining in the third quarter.

The Fever closed out the third quarter with a 7-2 run to make it
56-42.
